article.headline: Sprewell pours in 26 points
article.linkText: T-Wolves rally in fourth to beat Hornets
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Minnesota Timberwolves are looking comfortable pulling out tough victories in the fourth quarter. Down by 10 entering the final period Tuesday night, the Timberwolves got 12 points from Sam Cassell and timely baskets from Latrell Sprewell and Kevin Garnett to defeat the New Orleans Hornets 94-89. "We are one of the best executing ball clubs in the league in the fourth quarter," said Cassell, whose team has won 15 of 18 games. "We understand the concept of playing the whole ballgame." The Hornets, by contrast, shot 5-of-17 from the floor in the final period in losing their third straight. "We were pretty much in control for the most part," Hornets' guard Baron Davis said. "We have to close out the game better." Davis led New Orleans with 22 points but was streaky, going 8-of-23 from the field. His late 3-pointer gave New Orleans an 86-83 lead, but he missed on a drive and a jumper in the last two minutes. Latrell Sprewell scored 26 points, including a pair of key free throws with 14.5 seconds left to make it a two-possession game. He was 9-of-18 from the field and 6-of-7 from the line. He hit a 3-pointer with under five minutes to go to trim the Hornets' lead to 81-80. Kevin Garnett added 22, including a tough baseline turnaround jumper over the Hornets' P.J. Brown that gave Minnesota its first lead with 1:44 left in the game. "I do not think I could have defended him any better," Brown said. "It was a heck of a shot. He did what I wanted him to do, but that's why he's the superstar he is." Sam Cassell finished with 24, including a 3-pointer that tied the game at 83-83 with 2:44 left. "I told our guys when the fourth quarter started, 'We will win this game if we get a push right now. We need some pace into the game," Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "We can get a couple of quick buckets, get ourselves within striking distance and rely on ability to execute down the stretch, which has been huge for us over these last 20 games." After the Hornets went over the team foul limit with 3:14 to play, the Timberwolves went 9-of-12 from the foul line for nine of their last 14 points. Hornets center Jamaal Magloire hit three of four free throws to tie the score at 89-89 with 48 seconds left. But Fred Hoiberg gave his team the lead for good, 91-89, when he hit a pair of free throws with 31.5 seconds to go. Before the game, Hornets coach Tim Floyd said slow starts and first-quarter deficits had been a common theme in New Orleans' last six losses. He wanted that to change, and it did as the Hornets took a 30-18 lead in the opening quarter by shooting 12-of-17. The Hornets shot 58 percent in the first half, but saw their lead dwindle to 47-45 at halftime because of eight second-quarter turnovers. "The last two games we could have faulted our effort in the first quarter. Our effort was outstanding for four quarters tonight," Floyd said. "They had a couple players that stepped up and made big shots for them. It is frustrating."

Game notes
Minnesota has won four straight going into Wednesday night's game at defending champion San Antonio. ... Floyd spent the past couple days with Minnesota center Ervin Johnson, whom Floyd coached and essentially taught basketball at the University of New Orleans. Johnson, who is 6-foot-11, had never played in an organized league and was bagging groceries when Floyd decided to try him out. On Tuesday night, the two sat together at Lakefront Arena as UNO hosted LSU.
